A 2014 survey by the UK Employment and Training Commission found that 17 per cent of the reasons why employers are being tortured to fill vacancies can be attributed to a lack of language skills.
Therefore, language skills are becoming increasingly necessary in preparing young people for their future career path.
When it comes to future employment opportunities that require language skills, these skills are essential in the global world.
If someone learns another language, regardless of the career path they choose, with such lifelong knowledge, they have a great advantage in the future.
A multilingual person who can communicate directly with people from foreign countries has an automatic advantage over competition.
A 2013 YouGov survey of more than 4,000 adults in the UK found that 75 percent of people did not speak a foreign language well enough to speak, with French being the only language spoken by 15 percent, a two-person percentage point.
Therefore, investing in language learning is important for today’s children.
By learning more languages, especially those from developing economies, children have a better chance of finding the right job.
In Scotland, schools differ in the languages they teach.
Many schools focus on more classical modern languages, while others teach languages that are expected to be the most important for the UK in 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Regardless of your child’s interests, it will always be possible to choose a number of languages taught by professionals in this field in independent schools.
Scotland’s independent schools are committed to providing a learning environment that will prepare and equip children with the knowledge they need to succeed, regardless of what the future brings.
In a global business environment, it cannot be denied that languages remain extremely important for the future of the country, so this must also be expressed in education.
