“Without confidence in the United States, we will not be confident in state security and under such conditions, we will not be the first to unilaterally disarm.”
While Ri reiterated North Korea’s well-known complaints about Washington’s resistance to a protracted approach to nuclear disarmament, in which North Korea would be rewarded for adopting protracted measures, his statement was an important step in the process because it did not immediately become a matter of urgency.
Ri made a joint statement by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump from the first summit between the current U.S. president and the North Korean leader held in Singapore on June 12, at which time Kim pledged to strive for a "nuclear disarmament of the Korean peninsula."
North Korea wants an official end to the Korean War, which took place between 1950 and 1953, but the United States said Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also refused to allow calls for the release of stringent international sanctions that apply to North Korea.
“The U.S. insists that we must first nuclear disarmament, and escalates the pressure with sanctions in order to achieve its goals by force, and even opposes the declaration of the end of the war,” Ri said.
“The idea that sanctions could put us on our knees is an unrealistic hope for people who don’t know us at all.
