Red tide news: Concentrations off the coasts of Pinellas, Manatee and Saratosa districts are decreasing
The latest report by the Florida Fish and Wildlife Conservation Commission (FWC) shows a general reduction in red tide concentrations in parts of the Tampa Bay area.
The FWC Commission has reported more widespread flowering in the areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Saratosa, Charlotte and Collier, indicating a reduction in concentrations.
The red tide stretches about 130 miles from the north coast of Pinellas County to the south of Lee County.
The bills look about 10 miles off the coast of Hillsborough County, but in fewer places than last week.
Red tides have also been observed in Pasco district.
Last week, there were reported average concentrations in the County of Pinellas and along its coast, low to high concentrations on the Hillsborough coast, basic to high concentrations in the County of Manatee, and concentrations in the County of Colts, and concentrations in the County of Saratoga.
Respiratory agitation continues to be reported from Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier districts.
There were no reports of respiratory irritation in Northwest Florida last week.
